{"title_page": "Francis Balfour (bishop)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}The [[Right Reverend]] '''Francis Balfour''' (b [[Sorrento]] 21 June 1846; d [[Mafeteng]] 3 February 1924) was [[Assistant Bishop|Assistant]] [[Anglican Diocese of the Free State|Bishop of Bloemfontein]] from 1910 until his death.<ref>''Bishop Balfour.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Tuesday, 5 February 1924; pg. 12; Issue 43567</ref>\n\nBalfour was educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]]; [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]; and [[Ripon College Cuddesdon|Cuddesdon]]. He was [[ordained]] [[deacon]] in 1872, and priest in 1874. After a [[Curate|curacy]] in [[Buckingham]] he went out as a [[missionary]], firstly to [[Basutoland]] and then to [[Mashonaland]].<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]] 1908 p64: London, [[Horace Cox]], 1908</ref> He was [[Archdeacon]] of [[Bloemfontein]] from 1901 until 1906; and of [[Basutoland]] from 1907 to 1922.\n<ref>{{Who's Who | surname = Balfour| othernames = Francis Richard Townley | id = U195346 | type = was | volume = 1920\u20132016 | edition = 2 March 2018 online | accessed = 2 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of Bloemfontein}}\n{{Bishops of Bloemfontein}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balfour, Francis Richard Townley}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:People from Sorrento]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Bloemfontein]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Basutoland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Bloemfontein]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Clan Balfour|Francis]]\n\n\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n{{UK-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}The [[Right Reverend]] '''Francis Balfour''' (b [[Sorrento]] 21 June 1846; d [[Mafeteng]] 3 February 1924) was [[Assistant Bishop|Assistant]] [[Anglican Diocese of the Free State|Bishop of Bloemfontein]] from 1910 until his death.<ref>''Bishop Balfour.'' [[The]] (London, England), Tuesday, 5 February 1924; pg. 12; Issue 43567</ref>\n\nBalfour was educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]]; [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]; and [[Ripon College Cuddesdon|Cuddesdon]]. He was [[ordained]] [[deacon]] in 1872, and priest in 1874. After a [[Curate|curacy]] in [[Buckingham]] he went out as a [[missionary]], firstly to [[Basutoland]] and then to [[Mashonaland]].<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]] 1908 p64: London, [[Horace Cox]], 1908</ref> He was [[Archdeacon]] of [[Bloemfontein]] from 1901 until 1906; and of [[Basutoland]] from 1907 to 1922.\n<ref>{{Who's Who | surname = Balfour| othernames = Francis Richard Townley | id = U195346 | type = was | volume = 1920\u20132016 | edition = 2 March 2018 online | accessed = 2 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of Bloemfontein}}\n{{Bishops of Bloemfontein}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balfour, Francis Richard Townley}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:People from Sorrento]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Bloemfontein]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Basutoland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Bloemfontein]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Clan Balfour|Francis]]\n\n\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n{{UK-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link (from date/issue number)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Balfour_(bishop)"}
